Using AWS CodeDeploy to Deploy a Webpage from GitHub to an EC2 Instance¶

Amazon provides a variety of web services, one of them is the Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2). EC2 provides scalable compute capacity in the cloud. Therefore, it balances computing power, memory and networking resources. EC2 allows users to configure a Virtual Machine (VM)/ instance to deploy application content. In this task, I show and explain how I hosted a webpage from GitHub to an instance in EC2.

1. Create IAM (Identity Access Management) Role¶

In the first step, I had to define the Identity Access Management (IAM) roles. IAM Roles are in principle IAM identities which can receive different permission rights to access different parts of AWS. However, a role is not associated to only one person but is rather intended to be assumable by anybody who needs the access rights. In my AWS account, I selected Roles and began to create a new role.

I created two roles. The first role/ identity is needed to connect to the EC2 instance (VM) and the other one is needed to connect to managed deployment service CodeDeploy. CodeDeploy let us deploy a variety of application content, such as the earlier mentioned webpage.

As you can see, I have created two new roles, namely “E2S3” to connect to the EC2 instance and “codedeployrole” to connect to AWS CodeDeploy.

2. Create and Launch EC2 Instance¶

First, I chose the AWS region us-east-1 as a closer zone/ region means less latency and better response time.

Then, I had to create a new security group. The security group acts as a virtual firewall and I can later use this group when creating my instance. For my security group, I allowed all inbound traffic via application protocol Hypertext Transfer Protocol (http) and the network protocol Secure Shell (SSH) as well as generally all outbound traffic.

After setting up my IAM roles and the security group, I began to create my instance. As I have mentioned earlier, an Amazon Machine Image (AMI) is needed to configure the virtual machine/ EC2 instance. The AMI includes an Operating System as well as any additional application that are needed as a foundation to run our code in that instance. I have chosen an Amazon Linux AMI image and selected an instance type that has not much computing power but does not charge me extra:

I have configured the instance to choose the previously specified IAM role “E2S3” that allows me to connect to the instance. Furthermore, I have added the following command to install the AWS CodeDeploy Agent installation my EC2 istance. This is necessary to be able to deploy our code later:

#!/bin/sh yum update yum install -y ruby cd /home/ec2-user aws s3 cp s3://aws-codedeploy-us-west-1/latest/install . chmod +x ./install ./install auto

I went on with the default storage and added the tag “Name” to the Key and “Web Server” to the Value to better access the instance later. Afterward, I chose my earlier created security group and created a key pair that is needed to access my instance The Key pair consists of a public key which is stored in AWS. This public key is the publicly available address of my instance. The second key is the private key that is needed to access the instance. I have downloaded the private key as a .pem fuel and saved it on my local computer.

Once the private key was saved, I could launch my instance in Amazon EC2:

3. Connecting to Instances using SSH¶

As I am using a Windows Computer and not a linux based computer, I cannot just use the .pem file and the terminal to connect to my instance. Two additional tools are needed to connect to my instance. I used Putty to connect to my instance but as putty requires the private key in a .ppk format, I had to use PuttyGen to convert the key first.

I launched PuttyGen, imported my key and converted it to a .ppk format. Afterward, I started PuTTY and added the host address of my instance. As you can see below, I have added the Public IPv4 address of my instance and chose the private key in .ppk format under Connection > SSH > Auth

I went on and logged in as “ec2-user”.

4. Setup your EC2 to host the web page¶

Once logged on, I run the following commands to install a web server (called Apache server) to be able to host my webpage on the instance:

sudo yum install -y httpd sudo service httpd start sudo service httpd restart

Now, I have the webserver running on my EC2 instance and I can deploy my application on that instance

5. Setup CodeDeploy¶

Therefore, I use AWS Codedeploy that automates the deployment of my code to Amazon EC2 for instance:

I created a new application and specified the platform that I am using:

Then, I needed my earlier specified role “codedeployrole” to be able to connect to codedeploy. I chose “codedeployrole” as my service role and used the earlier added tags “Name” for Key and “web Server” for Value to identify my instance and chose to deploy all my code at once under the deployment settings.

After the deployment group was specified, I could go on and create the actual deployment. When creating the deployment, you can specify whether to code is stored in amazon storage (S3) or in github. As the webpage is stored in a github repository, I chose Github and added the github token name, github repository name and the commit ID. (The commit ID can be found in the github repository. In the list of commits, you can find the commit ID that refers to the revision in the repository).

Once everything was specified, I clicked on “Create deployment” and the webpage got deployed on my EC2 instance:

To access the webpage, you can look up the IPV4 Public IP of your EC2 instance and copy&paste the address into your browser:
